{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_start","contentIndex":1,"partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"          Based on my review of the record and evidence, I can now make my decision. The key evidence shows:\n\n1. Peter explicitly warned Samantha that he would only hold the rush printer slot if the package would be complete by the next evening\n2. Samantha responded that she had read Stephenson AND could deliver the finished package in time\n3. Peter relied on this representation to approve the rush printing\n4. Samantha later admitted she had not actually read the full essay before early drafts\n\nThe critical issue is whether Samantha's completion assurance was materially misleading when made. The confession shows she had not done the prerequisite reading she claimed to have done at the time she made the timing assurance. This false premise about the foundation of her work makes her completion timeline representation misleading under the assignment requirements.\n\nThe preponderance standard is met - it's more likely than not that her timing assurance was materially misleading and that Peter reasonably relied on it."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"019f149655f6048739d6b38bceb33775","name":"mcp","arguments":{},"partialArgs":"","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782756813237,"responseId":"gen-1782756813-PRS3Ti0LL5YYx8FEMkqE"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"          Based on my review of the record and evidence, I can now make my decision. The key evidence shows:\n\n1. Peter explicitly warned Samantha that he would only hold the rush printer slot if the package would be complete by the next evening\n2. Samantha responded that she had read Stephenson AND could deliver the finished package in time\n3. Peter relied on this representation to approve the rush printing\n4. Samantha later admitted she had not actually read the full essay before early drafts\n\nThe critical issue is whether Samantha's completion assurance was materially misleading when made. The confession shows she had not done the prerequisite reading she claimed to have done at the time she made the timing assurance. This false premise about the foundation of her work makes her completion timeline representation misleading under the assignment requirements.\n\nThe preponderance standard is met - it's more likely than not that her timing assurance was materially misleading and that Peter reasonably relied on it."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"019f149655f6048739d6b38bceb33775","name":"mcp","arguments":{},"partialArgs":"","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.1-terminus","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782756813237,"responseId":"gen-1782756813-PRS3Ti0LL5YYx8FEMkqE"}}
